Project_Description: Chemical treatment for maintenance control of Brazilian pepper, lead tree, melaleuca, Australian pine and melaleuca throughout 2,300 acres on the southern side of the base.  Invasive grasses were treated through foliar application, and the tree species were primarily treated through basal bark application to kill the plants in place.  Following the initial herbicide applications, contractors were responsible to retreat invasive plant species within the project area until the plants were completely dead.  No further removal or treatment was required after the invasive species were killed, and plants were left to breakdown over time.  In addition, mechanical clearing of Brazilian pepper was accomplished on a 30 acre site which included an area of gopher tortoise habitat in the south central portion of the base.  MacDill also accomplished a formal survey of invasive species coverage throughout the 2,300 wooded acres being managed for control of invasive species.
Habitat_Description: Pine forest areas are largely historic planted pine which has not been managed for timber.  Areas of oak hammock and mangrove lined ditches are scattered throughout the pine areas and mangrove esturary predominates along the southern boundary of the site.  Additionally, there are large tracts of land within the site that have been historically disturbed (former landfill areas) which are highly invaded with Brazilian pepper.  Brazilian pepper, melaleuca, and lead tree are commonly found along the forest edges and scattered throughout the understory.  Open fields have scattered areas of cogan grass.

There were 10 large ear pod trees on the eastern berm of Channel A that were cut down and all biomass removed from the site. Stumps were treated with herbicide to prevent re-sprouting. A skid steer with a forestry mulcher was used to clear non-native vegetation on the western Channel A berm and on the firelanes in the uplands. Areas were then treated with herbicide.

Project_Name: Ignacio Haya Park Living Shoreline Project
Project_Description: This 2,200 linear feet of park has mild to excessive erosion caused by boat wakes. This erosion has undercut the native trees, washed out the native plants/sediments, and this site has pockets of non-native vegetation. These issues were all addressed by implementing a Living Shoreline (LS) treatment, consisting of narrow band of rock placed approximately 10 feet from the original shoreline; these rocks will disrupt the boat wakes, allowing the banks to be restored with sediment and native wetland plants. Installed species included Spartina alterniflora, S. bakeri, S. patens, muhly grass, and dune sunflower.
Habitat_Description: Oligohaline shoreline section of the Hillsborough River (eastside, just below the Hillsborough Aveune bridge). Boat wake derived shoreline erosion  negatively affecting native marsh at this passive linear park.
Habitat_Type: Tidal Wetland: Sheltered waters along the coast which are affected by both tides and freshwater run-off.
Main_Funding_Source: Primary Funding Source: TBERF ($76K), EPC ($47K), City of Tampa ($30K), & ERI ($8K)

Project_Name: Sun City Center Nature Trail Invasives Control
Project_Description: Eradication of invasive exotic species within a 15-acre tract owned by the Sun City Center Community Association and the adjoining storm water conveyance owned by Hillsborough County that connects Cypress Creek and North Lake. Invasives include but are not limited to: water hyacinth, Japanese climbing fern, cogon grass, ear pod tree, carrotwood, Peruvian primrose, and Brazilian pepper. Treatment of the banks of the canal at the approach to the trail entry point consisted of foliar spraying and then manual cutting/mowing the dead vegetation. Periodic spraying and cutting will be required to maintain the current condition. Proceeding to the interior of the property, the contractor removed a large number of exotic trees, consisting of mostly carrot wood and camphor. Exotic trees up to 6 inches in diameter were felled and removed. The stumps of removed trees were treated with herbicide. Larger trees were girdled and treated. Access to the interior was cleared and widened to expedite continued restoration and maintenance. A stand of Brazilian pepper lined the property line behind the residential homes on Del Webb West. In addition, several earpod trees and some large camphor trees were located along the property line. The chemical Triclopyr @ 9% solution with basal oils was used for stump and basal treatments and glyphosate was used @ ¾ - 2% solution depending on what was being sprayed.
Habitat_Description: This project proposes the ground eradication of invasive exotic species within a 15 acre tract owned by the Sun City Center Community Association.
Author: XGRAULER

Project_Name: Ignacio Haya Linear Park - Wetland Restoration/Stormwater Improvement Project
Project_Description: This second phase effort addressed the southern former creek that had been ditch in the 1950s to restore the creek bed and create a biological treatment wetland to help remove nutrients prior to enter the Hillsborough River. Primary goals are to improve water quality by creating a biological treatments system, stabilizing the shoreline to reduce sediment pollution that the unprotected shoreline is creating and to restore the associated wetland vegetation. The design and permitting of all phases was paid for by a Pollution Recovery Grant in 2017.
Habitat_Description: Former creek was ditched to the Hillsborough River (southend of this park). Project restored/created a wetland area for habitat values as well as providing additional wetland plants to filter untreated stormwater runoff prior to entering the river.

Project_Description: The goal of this project is to create approximately 2,065 linear feet of oyster reef along MacDills eastern shoreline through the installation of 245 feet of concrete oyster domes, 1,120 feet of oyster shell bags, & 700 feet of oyster shell bags guarded by oyster domes directly in front of them. Project_Description: The goal of Tampa Bay Watch’s Community Oyster Reef Enhancement (CORE) program is to increase oyster populations in Tampa Bay while providing habitats for small organisms, preventing erosion, improving water quality, and promoting fish and wildlife habitats. The 2D Island Phase 2 Oyster Reef Creation Project consisted of the installation of oyster shell bags placed in the intertidal zone beneath the canopy of the mangroves. Each oyster shell bag was filled with fossilized shells and laid perpendicular to the shoreline in various arrangements based on substrate stability and shoreline slope. The shell bags were transported (by boat), unloaded, and placed at 2D Island by Tampa Bay Watch staff and volunteers .
Habitat_Description: 2D Island is a large spoil island located in Hillsborough Bay east of the mouth of the Alafia River. 2D Island was created in the late 1970’s as part of the Harbor Deepening Project.  It is situated on the east side of the main channel into Port Tampa Bay and the north side of the channel into the Riverview Mosaic berth. Much of the eastern shoreline consists of mangrove habitat which has been eroding due to wave energy from increased ship and boat wake in the area, as well as from storm events.
Project_Benefits:
Erosion Control
Improve or protect water quality
Partners: Environmental Protection Commission of Hillsborough County

Project_Name: Abercrombie Park Oyster Bar Creation Project
Project_Description: The goal of Tampa Bay Watch’s Community Oyster Reef Enhancement program is to increase oyster populations in Tampa Bay, while providing habitats for small organisms, preventing erosion, improving water quality and promoting fish and wildlife habitats. The Abercrombie Park Living Shoreline Creation Project consists of the installation of two types of substrate that provide a hard surface for oyster larvae to settle upon and grow, eventually forming a functioning reef: oyster reef balls (ORB) and oyster shell bags filled with fossilized and recycled oyster shell. The ORB fields will be constructed waterward of the oyster shell reefs and along mangroves to provide wave attenuation for erosion control and habitat for marine life.
Habitat_Description: Abercrombie Park is a small historically significant park located on the west coast of Pinellas county.  The pertinent benthic habitat consist of a mixture of soft (silt/sand), semi-soft (loose sand), shell hash.  All three benthic types were present within the footprint of this project.

Project_Name: Boyd Hill Nursery Field Restoration Project
Project_Description: This long term restoration project hopes to transform an unmanaged uplands field to a native meadow. We are phasing the 8.5 acre restoration project out into manageable units. Previous units were prepped using herbicide applications. This current unit of .17 acres was solarized for 2+ months before planting. Nine varieties of native grasses were planted; a mix of plugs and one gallon pots. These initial units are giving us information on what plant varieties are most successful and what site prep techniques give us the best results. This info will determine the direction of the next plantings and restoration units.
Habitat_Description: Site was previously used as a municipal nursery, after decommission the area was returned to unmanaged field/meadow of approx. 8.5 acres. The site now has open access to hikers and park users as a trail system goes through it.

Project_Description: The goal of Tampa Bay Watch’s Community Oyster Reef Enhancement program is to increase oyster populations in Tampa Bay while improving water quality, reducing erosion, promoting fish and wildlife habitats, and increasing coastal resilience. The Lassing Park Living Shoreline Creation Project consists of the installation of two types of substrate (Lo-Pro Reef Ball™ units and oyster shell bags filled with fossilized shell) for oyster larvae to settle upon and grow, eventually forming a functioning reef:. Sporobolus alterniflorous was also planted. The oyster reef ball fields were constructed waterward of the oyster shell reefs and along mangroves to provide wave attenuation for erosion control and habitat for marine life.
Habitat_Description: The pertinent habitat located within the footprint of the Lassing Park Living Shoreline project consists of hard pack sand and soft sediment (silt/sand). Lassing park is a public use park.  As one of the few unarmored shorelines, this area is inundated with high energy from both wind driven and boat driven wave action.  Resulting in a substantial erosion issue at the northern end of the park.
Project_Benefits:
Erosion Control
Improve or protect water quality
Author: NA

Project_Name: Mirror Lake Gateway Demonstration Project - Restoring Urban Lake Shorelines Through Volunteer Action
Project_Description: Funded by sales from the Tampa Bay Estuary specialty license plate, this project removed 1307 lbs of invasive debris were removed from the lake and surrounding area. Over 4 planting days, volunteers installed 485 native plants and 235 Florida native emergent wetland plants. In the upland area, Fakhahatchee grass, blanket flower, muhly grass and seaside ox-eye were planted.
Habitat_Description: Mirror Lake in St. Petersburg has experienced over a century of disturbance and use as passive recreational parkland. The lake shoreline presented a clear opportunity to restore natural biological diversity and littoral zone ecological function. The goal of the project was to demonstrate an approach to reversing the current condition and establish a self-sustaining stand of native vegetation in place of the existing mixed composition of native and invasive species.

Project_Description: The Philippe Park Living Shoreline Project focused on enhancing the shoreline at Philippe Park to reduce erosion and protect park property from sea level rise and storm surge; to improve water quality in Old Tampa Bay; to increase aquatic and shoreline habitat for oysters and other benthic organisms, fish, and wading birds; and to educate park visitors about living shorelines and coastal resiliency. Oyster bags were placed along two shoreline areas at Philippe Park (1,230 lf) from Oct 2021 through Apr 2022, and Spartina was planted as well. Habitat_Description: Oyster habitat in the form of shell bags and loose shell was built along the shoreline as well as offshore at Philippe Park. Spartina was planted along the shoreline as well.

Project_Name: Submerged Aquatic Vegetation (SAV) Planting at Bay Vista Park - Prop Scar Repair Plantings
Project_Description: Ecosphere was awarded funding to install SAV statewide to help expand the limits of SAV and this site was selected as a recipient site.  One acre of native shoal grass was installed within several blow holes and former prop scars that had sediment tubes inserted the year prior to accelerate the repair of this seagrass bed.  The shoal grass used for this effort was harvested from this region and then hand installed by hand to inoculate these former prop scares.
Habitat_Description: This area had multiple prop scars that TBW repaired with sediment tubes in 2023, however no SAV had naturally colonized these prop scars, although the conditions were good for SAV.  Ecosphere was awarded funding to install SAV statewide to help expand the limits of SAV and so this site was selected as a recipient site.

Project_Description: Ecosphere was awarded funding to install SAV statewide to help expand the limits of SAV and this site was selected as a recipient site. Project_Name: Boyd Hill Nature Preserve Freshwater Wetland Habitat Restoration
Project_Description: The project consists of construction of freshwater wetlands and coastal uplands within the Boyd Hill Nature Preserve in Pinellas County, Florida. Work includes excavation and embankment of two existing streams, re-contouring the stream bed and grading of side slopes to form ditch blocks and littoral shelves, installation and maintenance of existing culverts and stormwater conveyance structures, regrading an existing swale, and hydroblasting spoil berms into adjacent areas. The berms will require limited removal of exotic vegetation for access and clearing for planting areas. The creek bank will be planted with native species according to the planting plan. The measurable benefit is natural system creation/restoration of 30-acres.
Habitat_Description: The project consisted of modifying existing stormwater channels and back-filling ditches to restore natural flow and create wetland habitat and upland habitats within Boyd Hill Nature Preserve.
Project_Benefits:
Protect/improve/provide habitat for other wildlife
Restore natural hydrology

City of St. Petersburg
Tampa Bay Estuary Program

Project_Name: City of Treasure Island Living Shoreline
Project_Description: The living shoreline project was initiated to address ongoing issues with a failing seawall and erosion, habitat loss, and declining water quality along a vulnerable stretch of the Treasure Bay shoreline.  To protect and restore this coastal zone, a living shoreline approach was implemented using a combination of native marsh plantings and rip rap was strategically placed to reduce wave energy, trap sediments, and encourage natural vegetation growth. The intended outcomes of the project include stabilizing the shoreline, improving water quality, increasing biodiversity, and creating a self-sustaining, resilient habitat that can adapt to future environmental changes.
Habitat_Description: This living shoreline is a naturally stabilized coastal edge that mimics the structure and function of native shoreline ecosystems. It is characterized by a gentle, sloping transition between land and water, allowing for regular tidal flooding and dynamic sediment movement. The shoreline will be planted with salt-tolerant native vegetation, which help anchor the soil and provide vital habitat for fish, crabs, birds, and other wildlife.
Project_Benefits:

Project_Name: Cockroach Bay Nature Preserve, Supplemental Native Planting
Project_Description: The site is located within 1 mile of Cockroach Bay in the Ruskin area, just south of the Little Manatee River.  It provides habitat for coastal species and overwintering habitat for migratory songbirds.  Surveys done following prescribed burn conducted in June 2025 found 37 active gopher tortoise burrows on these former pinelands.  The goal is to continue to add native grasses and forbs to attain a more functional habitat for species present.  Over 12,000 individuals of native grasses, shrubs, trees and forbs were installed.
Habitat_Description: From 1943 -1992, the site was cropped. Restoration started on this management unit in 1993 with the introduction of pines and oaks. The site was routinely burned and invasive vegetation treated, including a few extended contract events. Several plantings have been conducted to increase native ground cover and reduce nuisance and invasive grasses and forbs. Site prep consisted of chemically spraying guinea grass, prexalis, rosary pea and others, and a prescribed burn about 3 weeks before planting

Project_Name: DeSoto Park Shoreline Enhancement & Outreach Project
Project_Description: The project is in McKay Bay, connected to Tampa Bay. Restoration activities included removal of invasive/nuisance vegetation from the shoreline. Stumps were treated with herbicide via basal bark method and grinded. Planting of native shoreline vegetation, after jute cloth installation, followed. Anticipated outcomes include recruitment of desirable salt-tolerant vegetation, including mangroves; strengthening of shoreline stability; and creating habitat for flora and fauna. Education signage and bat boxes were installed throughout the park to provide community residents with the opportunity to explore environmental issues, while bat populations will control insect populations, pollinate plants, and spread seed.

DeSoto Park offers various means of recreation: athletic fields, a Community Center that houses a computer lab, and plenty outdoor space with a picnic shelter, playground, skate park, and pool. The project site lies adjacent to the nature trail, providing shade and green space.

Project_Name: Newman Branch Canal Living Shoreline Tidal Creek Restoration Project
Project_Description: These canals have steep, unstable slopes that could be improved by transforming them into living shorelines.  Ecosphere offered to assist by securing grant funding from the TBEP to design and permit the implementation of a nature-based shoreline stabilization approach.  The resultant design also including creating a tidal creek system behind the former steep shoreline to increase estuarine habitat and provide a nursery ground for juvenile fisheries.  This resultant project not only improves fisheries, it also provides water quality improvements with the addition of the tidal creek system with native estuarine plants that will absorb nutrients. Another successful P3 project!
Habitat_Description: In 1973 this man-made canal was dug to provide boat access to middle Tampa Bay.   These canals had very steep slopes with limited native estuarine species.  Tampa Bay Electric Company now owns a section of these canals and wanted to transform it to a more natural stabile slope.

Project_Name: Philippe Park Oyster Reef Wave Attenuation Barriers
Project_Description: Oyster habitat has been greatly reduced in Tampa Bay, and restoring this habitat, especially in Old Tampa Bay, is a goal for the area. Four reef dome wave attenuation barrier arrays were installed just offshore of Philippe Park to create wildlife habitat (mainly for oyster recruitment) and increase shoreline resiliency. A total of 76 precast concrete reef domes were placed to create approximately 2,432 sq ft of habitat. 32 of the domes were 3 ft tall by 4 ft diameter, and 44 of the domes were 3 ft tall by 5 ft diameter. A contractor placed 6 inches of crushed concrete base and then installed the domes to designed specs using a barge and heavy machinery.
Habitat_Description: Precast concrete oyster domes were installed to provide hard substrate for oyster recruitment and enhance wildlife habitat in an intertidal cove area just offshore of Philippe Park.

Project_Description: Three different elements were installed approximately 20 feet waterward of the existing seawall at Philippe Park to create oyster habitat and reduce erosion along the wall due to wave energy. Arrays of oyster castle blocks, an innovative concrete product from Virginia, were placed along 325 linear feet. 178 basalt mesh bags were filled with recycled oyster shell and placed along approximately 50 linear feet in a pyramid design with 4 bags on the bottom, then 3 bags, then 2 bags. Another 80 linear ft of plastic mesh oyster shell bags were installed as well. Oyster recruitment will be monitored.

Project_Description: When the Roosevelt Creek Ch 5 salinity weir was constructed in 1979, it interrupted the natural ebb and flow of nutrients between the watersheds and Old Tampa bay. This weir was identified as a prime candidate for modification to restore its marine connection, allowing for the passage of biota and a more natural hydrologic connection between the upstream channel and Tampa Bay. The removal of invasive/exotic species and the establishment of native plantings, as well as the improved conditions for mangrove recruitment are also major benefits of the project. This connection also has the potential for manatee incursion, thus a manatee gate was installed as well as one-way grates on all pipes connected to the channel.
Habitat_Description: Stormwater runoff from nearby urban areas flows into the channel and reaches the weir, where it widens into stagnant open water before spilling over into a brackish system. Upstream, stagnation and low oxygen caused frequent cyanobacteria blooms and fish kills. The weir was often overtopped by seasonal, unnatural/flashy saline backflow from Tampa Bay. Downstream, the channel turns brackish, with red and black mangroves and dense Brazilian pepper at the water’s edge.
Project_Benefits:
Climate Change Adaption
Flood Control
Improve or protect water quality
Protect/improve/provide habitat for birds

Restore natural hydrology

Project_Description: We installed living shoreline breakwaters along 4 colonial waterbird nesting islands in Manatee County (Dot Dash Dit Critical Wildlife Area), and Pinellas County (Dogleg Key, Indian Rocks Beach Island, and Dunedin Sand Key West). The islands collectively host hundreds of pairs of nesting waterbirds from 15 species, including five state-threatened species and federally-threatened Wood Storks. To protect the islands from erosion and making them more resilient to sea level rise, we installed concrete reef ball breakwaters offshore to create a living shoreline. The linear arrays of reefballs are designed to be colonized by oysters, creating an artificial reef that provides wildlife and waterbird nesting habitat and improves water quality.
Habitat_Description: The islands are dredge spoil islands primarily vegetated with mangroves that have been experiencing erosion and toppling of mature mangroves due to vessel wakes, storms, and sea level rise.

Project_Description: Our contractor (AquaTech ECO Consultants) assessed the site for access and the best location to replant a portion of the SAV population; we selected an area along the eastern bank near the dam to install one acre of eelgrass. Due to the high concentration of alligators, the plants were installed via the distribution of "burritos" which consist of a bundle of eelgrass weighed with a small stone within a burlap sack.  This is the approved method that FWC uses in most of their freshwater lake SAV plantings. These were evenly distributed in the targeted area.
Habitat_Description: Taylor Lake located in Pinellas County formerly had both native and nonnative SAV covering the bottom of the lake; however in early 2025 the dam had to be replaced so the lake was drained for several months which killed all of the SAV.  Pinellas County requested that we install native SAV once the water levels returned to normal to help "jump start" the natural colonization of SAV.

Project_Name: Terra Ceia Preserve State Park Invasive Vegetation Control
Project_Description: This is a habitat restoration project at the 1,948 acre Terra Ceia Preserve State Park managed by the Florida Department of Environmental Protection. There is an approved management plan for the park and management focuses on habitat protection and restoration, as well as public access and recreation.  FY24-25 Habitat restoration activities completed included treatment of 51.98 acres of invasive vegetation within 272.39 gross acres of park property, planting of native vegetation, and trail maintenance.
Habitat_Description: Forested Woodland Upland Habitat
Lead_Implementer: Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission - Invasive Plant Management
Partners: Florida Department of Environmental Protection - Division of Recreation and Parks
Main_Funding_Source: Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission - Invasive Plant Management
Author: NA

Project_Description: This project focuses on selective herbicide application to Category 1 and 2 Florida Invasive Species Council's List of Invasive Plant Species within the conservation areas at Tom Bennett Park which includes areas of the park tidally connected to the Manatee River.
Habitat_Description: Manatee County's Natural Resources Department is tasked with managing Tom Bennett Park's conservation areas to reduce invasive and non-native plant cover.  The treatment of these invasive plants will support the native plant community and benefit wildlife.  Vegetation management is helping with the establishment of native trees planted in 2022 by reducing competition from non-native vegetation.

Project_Description: The project entailed removal of the spoil mounds and all nuisance species. The mosquito ditches were either filled with the excavated spoil material to black mangrove elevations, dredged to promote effective diurnal flushing, or desilted to remove organics. Ditch blocks were installed at the end of ditches that were filled to prevent the movement of the placed fill material into the dredged or desilted ditches.  Nuisance species were removed from a few isolated spoil mounds with difficult access and planted with native upland species. Additional areas that exhibited saltern conditions were planted with appropriate species. This project will encourage the recruitment of mangroves, restore tidal flows, and improve fisheries habitat.
Habitat_Description: The restoration site at Weedon Island Preserve consisted of mosquito ditches and spoil mounds among a black mangrove habitat.  While the mosquito ditching created some red mangrove habitat, most ditches exhibited poor water quality from limited flushing.  The impounded ditches captured organics up to two feet deep which caused anoxic conditions. Very limited wildlife utilization was observed during initial site surveys including an absence of fish.
